Now I understand. The new version uses virtual modules (`#tanstack-router-entry` which resolves to `app/router.tsx`). The `ssr.tsx` entry should now just be a server entry that exports the handler. Let me look at what the virtual `default-server-entry` generates:

Looking at the plugin code I found earlier:
```ts
getVirtualServerEntry(ctx) {
  return `
import { createStartHandler, defaultStreamHandler } from '@tanstack/react-start/server';
import { createRouter } from '${ctx.routerFilepath}';

export default createStartHandler({
  createRouter,
})(defaultStreamHandler);`;
}
```

This is the auto-generated entry. But this is only used when `startConfig.serverEntryPath` starts with `/~start/default-server-entry`. Otherwise, it uses the user's custom `ssr.tsx`. 

The key insight: in this new version (1.120.20), the framework has changed significantly. Instead of `ssr.tsx` having `createStartHandler({createRouter})`, the system uses virtual modules. Let me look at what the `createStartHandler` actually accepts:

The `createStartHandler` doesn't take `createRouter` anymore - it loads the router from virtual modules. So the `ssr.tsx` should just call `createStartHandler(defaultStreamHandler)`.

